So she completely overlooked the fact that more CO2 leads to more yield and plant growth, and instead focused on an unproven marginal reduction of some micronutrients in a handpicked selection of foods? How about she extends the graph as 1:30 and shows that CO2 used to be over 2000ppm in the Mesozoic period, and almost 5000ppm in the Paleozoic? Vegetation and animal life thrived in these periods. You know what will certainly harm the poorest in the world? Limiting their access to cheap energy which will trap them in eternal poverty.

@Aspergillus Oryzae The actual impact of micronutrient in food, if any, is entirely unknown. All you have is a handful of experiments that were not replicated by multiple scientists to develop a solid bibliography on the matter. It takes a serious volume of crop studies for you to eliminate all the other variables that could cause nutritional variance. And even the experiments that exist are based on estimates for what CO2 will be in the future, which is a completely wild guess. Even if there is a marginal reduction in micronutrients in some specific crops, there is no telling what that impact will be. People‚Äôs diet are ever changing, vitamin reduction is a specific food doesn‚Äôt mean reduction in the overall diet, or even a deficiency. Farming and fertilizer technologies are ever changing and wildly impact the crops nutrition. GMOs can create modified crops that have more nutrients, supplements become more and more cost effective, and so on. Restricting poor people‚Äôs access to *cheap energy,* on the other hand, does have a direct and huge impact on their ability to lift themselves out of poverty. Limiting carbon emission on developing countries (the biggest polluters even today) is literally the most damaging thing anyone could do.

More CO2 does lead to more yield to an extent, but it also requires more nutrients to sustain, and in the case of nonleaf crops especially, that would just be extra vegetation that disperses nutrients in the plant, making the crop more costly to maintain as well as making the plants less nutritious. The micronutrients you brush over aren't unimportant, btw. In impoverished areas, deficiencies of those micronutrients cause diseases when they can normally be found in healthy food. Think about how costly it is to treat diseases and how limited medical facilities can be in some of these less developed areas.
